<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<!DOCTYPE plist PUBLIC "-//Apple//DTD PLIST 1.0//EN" "http://www.apple.com/DTDs/PropertyList-1.0.dtd">
<plist version="1.0">
<dict>
    <!--
      Hardened-runtime entitlements for fbe-go.app.

      The hardened runtime is required by Apple's notarization service —
      binaries without it are rejected with "The executable does not have the
      hardened runtime enabled." Enabling it also locks down several runtime
      behaviors by default; any of those that we rely on must be re-allowed
      via a named entitlement below.

      What fbe-go.app actually does at runtime:
        1. Embeds a WebKit webview (Wails v2 on macOS uses WKWebView).
           WebKit JITs JavaScript — without allow-jit it would bail with
           a "JavaScript JIT is disabled" console message and every PM
           doc would crawl.
        2. Loads the Wails runtime JS into the webview; that module uses
           `eval`-style code paths (prosemirror commands, svelte HMR in
           dev). Under hardened runtime the WKWebView already handles
           this via the JIT entitlement — no need for
           cs.disable-executable-page-protection.
        3. Reads arbitrary user-chosen FB2 files via OpenFileDialog. In
           a hardened app without the Files entitlement set, the system
           policy-gates file access — we DO want that for sandboxing when
           we eventually add App Store distribution, but for Developer-ID
           distribution it's non-blocking because hardened runtime by
           default permits access to paths the user picks via a standard
           open panel.
        4. Executes NO external binaries (no `fc-list` fallback etc. on
           macOS — only Linux uses that path). No library-validation
           opt-out needed.

      What we DO NOT grant:
        - com.apple.security.cs.disable-library-validation: we only load
          libraries we signed or Apple-trusted system libraries.
        - com.apple.security.cs.allow-unsigned-executable-memory: the
          JIT entitlement is more specific and sufficient for WebKit.
        - network.client: Developer-ID apps don't need to declare this
          (only App Sandbox does). CheckForUpdate uses HTTPS to GitHub;
          this works without any entitlement on hardened-runtime.
        - files.* entitlements: same — only needed under App Sandbox.

      Sources:
        - https://developer.apple.com/documentation/security/hardened_runtime
        - https://wails.io/docs/guides/mac-app-store — notes allow-jit
          for WKWebView JS performance.
    -->

    <!-- Allow the WebKit JavaScriptCore JIT. Without this, the PM editor
         bogs down on medium/large FB2 docs because JS interpretation falls
         back to the baseline tier. -->
    <key>com.apple.security.cs.allow-jit</key>
    <true/>
</dict>
</plist>
